    <stitle>CALIPER DISC BRAKES - SERVICE PROCEDURES - CLEAN AND INSPECT CALIPER COMPONENTS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="clean" graphiccount="5">
        <title>CLEAN AND INSPECT CALIPER COMPONENTS</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using a wire brush, clean caliper sliding surfaces and piston bore area.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using a pick type tool be sure piston seal groove in caliper housing is free of all foreign
                materials (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401625">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401625" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401625" filename="../figg04/G0401625.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Typical Pick Tool</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HANDLE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. STEEL SHANK</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clean caliper housing with solvent. Air dry and check piston bore. If piston bore is not
                clean, use a fine grit emery cloth and lightly sand cylinder bore. Use compressed air to clean caliper
                assembly. Clean pistons with denatured alcohol.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check caliper pistons. If caliper being serviced has non-metallic piston (phenolic plastic)
                material, check the pistons for cracks, chips, gouges and heat damage.
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401626">Figure 26</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401627">Figure 27</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401628">Figure 28</hotlnk>
                illustrate the condition of these pistons, and if the piston should be replaced or can be reused.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401626" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401626" filename="../figg04/G0401626.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Phenolic Piston - Excessive Heat Damage</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0401627" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401627" filename="../figg04/G0401627.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Phenolic Piston - Crack, Chips and Gouges</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0401628" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401628" filename="../figg04/G0401628.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Phenolic Piston - Good Condition</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect caliper support key and spring. Replace if any signs of wear exist. Always replace
                key and spring together as a set (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401629">Figure 29</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401629" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401629" filename="../figg04/G0401629.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 29. Support Key and Spring Wear Points</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
